included.name: Eye Tracking Reveals How Oriental People Group Objects
included.publisher: CogSci 2012 (the 34th annual meeting of the Cognitive Science Society)
included.description: Our team wanted to look at how oriental people group objects differently than western people. An eye-tracking experiment (non-verbal instruction) was conducted to reveal how people fixate on objects. Some indexes were explored, such as first fixation duration, fixation counts, total fixation duration. Our results suggest that oriental people found it more natural to group things in thematic relationship.
